The compiler accepts calling other Iterator-Methods which require a owned self within Iterator methods which only have a &mut self.

```rust
struct MyIter;

impl Iterator for MyIter {
    type Item = usize;

    fn next(&mut self) -> Option<Self::Item> {
        self.count(); // Shouldn't be allowed!
        let _ = self.enumerate(); // Shouldn't be allowed!
        None
    }

    fn nth(&mut self, _n: usize) -> Option<Self::Item> {
        self.count(); // Shouldn't be allowed!
        let _ = self.enumerate(); // Shouldn't be allowed!
        None
    }

    fn size_hint(&self) -> (usize, Option<usize>) {
        //let x = self.count(); // Correctly  prohibits compilation
        //let x = self.enumerate(); // Correctly  prohibits compilation
        (0, Some(0))
    }
}

```


I expected to see a compiler error in this case.

Instead, it runs with undefined behavior...

This bug seems to affect just the Iterator-Trait. Custom traits are handled correctly.
```rust
trait NotAffected: Sized {
    fn test(&mut self) {
        //self.owned() // Correctly  prohibits compilation
    }
    fn owned(self) {}
}

impl NotAffected for MyIter {
    fn test(&mut self) {
        //self.owned() // Correctly  prohibits compilation
    }
}
```

